<p><b>Lexus</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji" lang="ja"></span><span class="t_nihongo_comma" style="display:none">,</span> <i>Rekusasu</i><sup class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><a href="/wiki/Help:Installing_Japanese_character_sets" title="Help:Installing Japanese character sets"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup>)</span> is the <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">luxury vehicle</a> division of Japanese car maker <a href="/wiki/Toyota" title="Toyota">Toyota</a>. The Lexus <a href="/wiki/Marque" class="mw-redirect" title="Marque">marque</a> is marketed in more than 70 countries and territories worldwide<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> and has become Japan's largest-selling make of premium cars. It has ranked among the 10 largest Japanese global <a href="/wiki/Brand" title="Brand">brands</a> in market value.<sup id="cite_ref-jbrand_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jbrand-2">[2]</a></sup> Lexus is headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Nagoya" title="Nagoya">Nagoya</a>, Japan. Operational centers are located in <a href="/wiki/Brussels" title="Brussels">Brussels</a>, <a href="/wiki/Belgium" title="Belgium">Belgium</a> and the U.S. in <a href="/wiki/Torrance,_California" title="Torrance, California">Torrance, California</a>.</p>
<p>Lexus originated from a corporate project to develop a new premium sedan, <a href="/wiki/Code-name" class="mw-redirect" title="Code-name">code-named</a> F1, which began in 1983 and culminated in the launch of the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS" title="Lexus LS">Lexus LS</a> in 1989. Subsequently, the division added <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Sedan (car)">sedan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coup">coup</a>, <a href="/wiki/Convertible_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Convertible (car)">convertible</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sport_utility_vehicle" title="Sport utility vehicle">SUV</a> models. Lexus did not exist as a brand in its home market until 2005, and all vehicles marketed internationally as Lexus from 1989 to 2005 were released in Japan under the Toyota marque and an equivalent model name. In 2005, a <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_vehicle" title="Hybrid vehicle">hybrid</a> version of the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX" title="Lexus RX">RX</a> crossover debuted and additional hybrid models later joined the division's lineup. Lexus launched its own <a href="/wiki/Lexus#F_marque" title="Lexus">F marque</a> performance division in 2007 with the debut of the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_IS_F" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus IS F">IS F</a> sport sedan, followed by the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LFA" title="Lexus LFA">LFA</a> supercar in 2009.</p>
<p>Lexus vehicles are largely produced in Japan, with manufacturing centered in the <a href="/wiki/Ch%C5%ABbu_region" title="Chbu region">Chbu</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ky%C5%ABsh%C5%AB" class="mw-redirect" title="Kysh">Kysh</a> regions, and in particular at Toyota's <a href="/wiki/Tahara_plant" title="Tahara plant">Tahara</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aichi_Prefecture" title="Aichi Prefecture">Aichi</a>, Chbu and <a href="/wiki/Miyata,_Fukuoka" title="Miyata, Fukuoka">Miyata</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fukuoka_Prefecture" title="Fukuoka Prefecture">Fukuoka</a>, Kysh plants. Assembly of the first Lexus built outside the country, the <a href="/wiki/Ontario" title="Ontario">Ontario</a>, <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a>produced RX 330, began in 2003. Following a corporate reorganization from 2001 to 2005, Lexus began operation of its own <a href="/wiki/Automotive_design" title="Automotive design">design</a>, <a href="/wiki/Automotive_engineering" title="Automotive engineering">engineering</a> and manufacturing centers.</p>
<p>Since the 2000s, Lexus has increased sales outside its largest market, the United States. The division inaugurated <a href="/wiki/Car_dealership" title="Car dealership">dealerships</a> in Japan's <a href="/wiki/Japanese_domestic_market" title="Japanese domestic market">domestic market</a> in 2005, becoming the first Japanese premium car marque to launch in its <a href="/wiki/Country_of_origin" title="Country of origin">country of origin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cbs_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbs-3">[3]</a></sup> The brand was introduced in <a href="/wiki/Southeast_Asia" title="Southeast Asia">Southeast Asia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Latin_America" title="Latin America">Latin America</a>, <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and other regions. The division's lineup also reflects regional differences for model and <a href="/wiki/Powertrain" title="Powertrain">powertrain</a> configurations.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1980s:_The_F1_project">1980s: The F1 project</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: 1980s: The F1 project">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 1983, Toyota chairman <a href="/wiki/Eiji_Toyoda" title="Eiji Toyoda">Eiji Toyoda</a> issued a challenge to build the world's best car.<sup id="cite_ref-m43_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m43-4">[4]</a></sup> The project, code-named F1 (Flagship One)<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> developed the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS" title="Lexus LS">Lexus LS 400</a> to expand Toyotas product line in the premium segment.<sup id="cite_ref-pr_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pr-6">[6]</a></sup> The F1 project followed the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Supra" title="Toyota Supra">Toyota Supra</a> sports car and the premium <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Mark_II" title="Toyota Mark II">Toyota Mark II</a> models.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> Both the Supra and Mark II were <a href="/wiki/Rear-wheel_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear-wheel drive">rear-wheel drive</a> cars with a powerful <a href="/wiki/Toyota_M_engine#7M-GE" title="Toyota M engine">7M-GE</a> or <a href="/wiki/Toyota_M_engine#7M-GTE" title="Toyota M engine">7M-GTE</a> inline-six engine. The largest sedan Toyota built at the time was the limited-production, 1960s-vintage <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Century" title="Toyota Century">Toyota Century</a>, a domestic, hand-built limousine, and V8-powered model,<sup id="cite_ref-d6_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d6-8">[8]</a></sup> followed by the inline-six-engined <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Crown_(S110)" class="mw-redirect" title="Toyota Crown (S110)">Toyota Crown</a> premium sedan.<sup id="cite_ref-d6_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d6-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-l16_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-l16-9">[9]</a></sup> The Century was conservatively styled for the Japanese market and along with the Crown not slated for export after a restyle in 1982.<sup id="cite_ref-l16_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-l16-9">[9]</a></sup> The F1 designers targeted their new sedan at international markets and began development on a new V8 engine.<sup id="cite_ref-d6_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d6-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-l16_9-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-l16-9">[9]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Car front view, halfway lit, with 15 champagne glasses stacked on the hood to form a triangle." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e2/Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg/220px-Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg" width="220" height="127" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/e/e2/Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg/330px-Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/e/e2/Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg 2x" data-file-width="344" data-file-height="199" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Balance_ad.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lexus <a href="/wiki/Balance_(advertisement)" title="Balance (advertisement)">television debut</a> with champagne glasses stacked on the hood of a revving <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS" title="Lexus LS">LS 400</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Japanese manufacturers exported more expensive models in the 1980s due to <a href="/wiki/Voluntary_Export_Restraints" class="mw-redirect" title="Voluntary Export Restraints">voluntary export restraints</a> negotiated by the Japanese government and U.S. trade representatives that restricted mainstream car sales.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> In 1986, <a href="/wiki/Honda" title="Honda">Honda</a> launched its <a href="/wiki/Acura" title="Acura">Acura</a> marque in the U.S., influencing Toyota's plans for a luxury division.<sup id="cite_ref-d109_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d109-11">[11]</a></sup> The initial Acura model was an export version of the <a href="/wiki/Honda_Legend" title="Honda Legend">Honda Legend</a>, itself launched in Japan in 1985 as a rival to the Toyota Crown, <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Cedric" title="Nissan Cedric">Nissan Cedric</a>/<a href="/wiki/Nissan_Gloria" title="Nissan Gloria">Gloria</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mazda_Luce" title="Mazda Luce">Mazda Luce</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> In 1987, <a href="/wiki/Nissan_Motor_Co.,_Ltd." class="mw-redirect" title="Nissan Motor Co., Ltd.">Nissan</a> unveiled its plans for a premium brand, <a href="/wiki/Infiniti" title="Infiniti">Infiniti</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-d72_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d72-13">[13]</a></sup> and revised its <a href="/wiki/Nissan_President" title="Nissan President">Nissan President</a> sedan in standard wheelbase form for export as the <a href="/wiki/Infiniti_Q45" title="Infiniti Q45">Infiniti Q45</a>, which it launched in 1990.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Mazda" title="Mazda">Mazda</a> began selling the Luce as the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_929" title="Mazda 929">Mazda 929</a> in North America in 1988 and later began plans to develop an upscale marque to be called <a href="/wiki/Amati_Cars" title="Amati Cars">Amati</a>, but its plans did not come to fruition.<sup id="cite_ref-d72_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d72-13">[13]</a></sup></p>
<p>Toyota researchers visited the U.S. in May 1985 to conduct <a href="/wiki/Focus_group" title="Focus group">focus groups</a> and <a href="/wiki/Market_research" title="Market research">market research</a> on luxury consumers.<sup id="cite_ref-d35_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d35-15">[15]</a></sup> During that time, several F1 designers rented a home in <a href="/wiki/Laguna_Beach,_California" title="Laguna Beach, California">Laguna Beach, California</a> to observe the lifestyles and tastes of <a href="/wiki/American_upper_class" title="American upper class">American upper class</a> consumers.<sup id="cite_ref-d35_15-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d35-15">[15]</a></sup> Meanwhile, F1 engineering teams conducted prototype testing on locations ranging from the German <a href="/wiki/Autobahn" title="Autobahn">autobahn</a> to U.S. roads.<sup id="cite_ref-ed_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ed-16">[16]</a></sup> Toyotas market research concluded that a separate <a href="/wiki/Brand_name" class="mw-redirect" title="Brand name">brand</a> and sales channel were needed to present its new sedan, and plans were made to develop a new network of dealerships in the U.S. market.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Brand_development">Brand development</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Brand development">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 1986, Toyotas longtime advertising agency <a href="/wiki/Saatchi_%26_Saatchi" title="Saatchi &amp; Saatchi">Saatchi &amp; Saatchi</a> formed a specialized unit, <a href="/wiki/Team_One_(advertising_agency)" title="Team One (advertising agency)">Team One</a>, to handle marketing for the new brand.<sup id="cite_ref-d109_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d109-11">[11]</a></sup> Image consulting firm <a href="/wiki/Lippincott_Mercer" class="mw-redirect" title="Lippincott Mercer">Lippincott &amp; Margulies</a> was hired to develop a list of 219 prospective names; Vectre, Verone, Chaparel, Calibre and Alexis were chosen as top candidates.<sup id="cite_ref-m57_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m57-18">[18]</a></sup> While Alexis quickly became the front runner, concerns were raised that the name applied to people more than cars (being associated with the <a href="/wiki/Alexis_Carrington" class="mw-redirect" title="Alexis Carrington">Alexis Carrington</a> character on the popular 1980s prime time drama <a href="/wiki/Dynasty_(TV_series)" title="Dynasty (TV series)"><i>Dynasty</i></a>).<sup id="cite_ref-m57_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m57-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-d111_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d111-19">[19]</a></sup> As a result, the first letter was removed and the "i" replaced with a "u" to morph the name to Lexus.<sup id="cite_ref-d111_19-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d111-19">[19]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a sedan parked on a street." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg/220px-Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg" width="220" height="118" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg/330px-Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg/440px-Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="550" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LS_400_UCF10_I.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS#XF10" title="Lexus LS">LS 400</a> sedan launched in 1989</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Theories of the etymology of the Lexus name have suggested it is the combination of the words "luxury" and "elegance,"<sup id="cite_ref-flex_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-flex-20">[20]</a></sup> and that it is an acronym for "luxury exports to the U.S."<sup id="cite_ref-flex_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-flex-20">[20]</a></sup> According to Team One interviews, the brand name has no specific meaning and simply denotes a luxurious and technological image.<sup id="cite_ref-m57_18-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m57-18">[18]</a></sup> Prior to the release of the first vehicles, database service <a href="/wiki/LexisNexis" title="LexisNexis">LexisNexis</a> obtained a temporary <a href="/wiki/Injunction" title="Injunction">injunction</a> forbidding the name Lexus from being used because it might cause product confusion.<sup id="cite_ref-d130_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d130-21">[21]</a></sup> The injunction threatened to delay the division's launch and marketing efforts.<sup id="cite_ref-d130_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d130-21">[21]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/U.S._appeals_court" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. appeals court">U.S. appeals court</a> lifted the injunction, deciding that there was little likelihood of confusion between the two products.<sup id="cite_ref-d130_21-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d130-21">[21]</a></sup></p>
<p>The original Lexus slogan, developed after Team One representatives visited Lexus designers in Japan and noted an obsessive attention to detail, became "<i>The Relentless Pursuit of Perfection.</i>"<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> The Lexus logo was developed by Molly Designs and Hunter Communications.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> The final design for the Lexus logo featured a stylized <i>L</i> within an oval, and according to Toyota, was rendered using a mathematical formula.<sup id="cite_ref-m57_18-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m57-18">[18]</a></sup> The first teaser ads featuring the Lexus name and logo appeared at the Chicago, Los Angeles and New York auto shows in 1988.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch">Launch</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Launch">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The F1 project was completed in 1989, involving 60 designers, 24 engineering teams, 1,400 engineers, 2,300 technicians, 220 support workers, approximately 450 prototypes and more than $1 billion in costs.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> The resulting car, the Lexus LS 400, had a design that shared no major elements with previous Toyota vehicles, with a new 4.0 L <a href="/wiki/V8_engine" title="V8 engine">V8</a> <a href="/wiki/Four-stroke_cycle" class="mw-redirect" title="Four-stroke cycle">gasoline engine</a> and <a href="/wiki/Rear-wheel_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear-wheel drive">rear-wheel drive</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-m31_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m31-28">[28]</a></sup> The car debuted in January 1989 at the <a href="/wiki/North_American_International_Auto_Show" title="North American International Auto Show">North American International Auto Show</a> in Detroit<sup id="cite_ref-d72_13-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d72-13">[13]</a></sup> and sales of the vehicle began the following September at a network of 81 new Lexus dealerships in the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> The LS 400 was sold along with the smaller <a href="/wiki/Lexus_ES" title="Lexus ES">ES 250</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Rebadging" title="Rebadging">rebadged</a> version of the Japanese market <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Camry#V20" title="Toyota Camry">Toyota Camry Prominent/Toyota Vista</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ed_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ed-16">[16]</a></sup> The launch of Lexus was accompanied by a multimillion-dollar advertising campaign.<sup id="cite_ref-d118_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d118-30">[30]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a coupe." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg/220px-Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg" width="220" height="113" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg/330px-Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4e/Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg 2x" data-file-width="381" data-file-height="196" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_SC_400_1991.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
1991 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_SC#Z30" title="Lexus SC">SC 400</a> coupe was the third Lexus model</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The LS 400 was praised for its quietness, well-appointed and <a href="/wiki/Ergonomic" class="mw-redirect" title="Ergonomic">ergonomic</a> interior, engine performance, build <a href="/wiki/Quality_(business)" title="Quality (business)">quality</a>, <a href="/wiki/Aerodynamics" title="Aerodynamics">aerodynamics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" title="Fuel economy in automobiles">fuel economy</a> and value.<sup id="cite_ref-ed_16-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ed-16">[16]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-d68_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d68-31">[31]</a></sup> However, it was criticized by some automobile columnists for derivative styling and a <a href="/wiki/Suspension_(vehicle)" title="Suspension (vehicle)">suspension</a> regarded as too compromising of handling for ride comfort.<sup id="cite_ref-ed_16-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ed-16">[16]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-32">[32]</a></sup> In some markets it was priced against mid-size, six-cylinder <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz" title="Mercedes-Benz">Mercedes-Benz</a> and <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a> models.<sup id="cite_ref-com_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-com-33">[33]</a></sup> It was rated by <i><a href="/wiki/Car_and_Driver" title="Car and Driver">Car and Driver</a></i> magazine as better than the higher-priced Mercedes-Benz <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W126" title="Mercedes-Benz W126">420 SEL</a> and BMW <a href="/wiki/BMW_E32" class="mw-redirect" title="BMW E32">735i</a> in terms of ride, handling and performance.<sup id="cite_ref-zen_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zen-34">[34]</a></sup> The LS 400 also won <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS_awards_list" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus LS awards list">motoring awards</a> from automotive publications including <i><a href="/wiki/Automobile_Magazine" class="mw-redirect" title="Automobile Magazine">Automobile Magazine</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Wheels_Magazine" class="mw-redirect" title="Wheels Magazine">Wheels Magazine</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> Lexus quickly established customer loyalty and its debut was generally regarded as a shock to existing luxury marques. BMW's and Mercedes-Benz's U.S. sales figures dropped 29 percent and 19 percent, respectively, with BMW executives accusing Lexus of <a href="/wiki/Dumping_(pricing_policy)" title="Dumping (pricing policy)">dumping</a> in that market, while 35 percent of Lexus buyers traded in a Lincoln or Cadillac.<sup id="cite_ref-zen_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zen-34">[34]</a></sup></p>
<p>In December 1989, Lexus initiated a voluntary recall of all 8,000 LS 400s based upon two customer complaints over defective <a href="/wiki/Wiring" class="mw-redirect" title="Wiring">wiring</a> and an overheated <a href="/wiki/Brake_light" class="mw-redirect" title="Brake light">brake light</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-zen_34-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zen-34">[34]</a></sup> A 20-day operation to replace the parts on affected vehicles included technicians to pick up, repair and return cars to customers free of charge, and also flying personnel and renting garage space for owners in remote locations.<sup id="cite_ref-zen_34-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zen-34">[34]</a></sup> This response was covered in media publications and helped establish the marque's early reputation for <a href="/wiki/Customer_service" title="Customer service">customer service</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<p>By the end of 1989, a total of 16,392 LS 400 and ES 250 sedans were sold in the four months following the U.S. launch.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup> Although sales had begun at a slower pace than expected, the final tally matched the division's target of 16,000 units for that year.<sup id="cite_ref-dw125_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dw125-40">[40]</a></sup> Following initial models, plans called for the addition of a sports coupe along with a redesigned ES sedan.<sup id="cite_ref-dw141_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dw141-41">[41]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="1990s:_Growth_and_expansion">1990s: Growth and expansion</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: 1990s: Growth and expansion">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus.RX.300.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of an SUV." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Lexus.RX.300.jpg/220px-Lexus.RX.300.jpg" width="220" height="121" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Lexus.RX.300.jpg/330px-Lexus.RX.300.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Lexus.RX.300.jpg/440px-Lexus.RX.300.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2176" data-file-height="1200" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus.RX.300.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
1998 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX#XU10" title="Lexus RX">RX 300</a>, first Lexus crossover SUV</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1990, during its first full year of sales, Lexus sold 63,594 LS 400 and ES 250 sedans in the U.S.,<sup id="cite_ref-d139_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d139-42">[42]</a></sup> the majority being the LS model.<sup id="cite_ref-d139_42-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d139-42">[42]</a></sup> That year, Lexus also began limited exports to the United Kingdom, Switzerland, Canada and Australia.<sup id="cite_ref-ed_16-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ed-16">[16]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[43]</a></sup> In 1991, Lexus launched its first sports coupe, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_SC" title="Lexus SC">SC 400</a>, which shared the LS 400s V8 engine and rear-wheel drive design.<sup id="cite_ref-dw141_41-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dw141-41">[41]</a></sup> This was followed by the second generation <a href="/wiki/Lexus_ES#Second_generation_.28VCV10.29" title="Lexus ES">ES 300</a> sedan, which succeeded the ES 250 and became Lexus' top seller.<sup id="cite_ref-dw141_41-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dw141-41">[41]</a></sup> At the conclusion of 1991, Lexus had become the top-selling premium car import in the U.S.,<sup id="cite_ref-msntl_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msntl-44">[44]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Long_2001.2C_p._51_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Long_2001.2C_p._51-45">[45]</a></sup> with sales reaching 71,206 vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-d139_42-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d139-42">[42]</a></sup> That year, Lexus ranked highest in <a href="/wiki/J.D._Power_and_Associates" title="J.D. Power and Associates">J.D. Power and Associates</a>' studies on initial vehicle quality, customer satisfaction and sales satisfaction for the first time.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> The marque also began increasing U.S. model prices past those of comparable American premium makes, but still below high-end European models.<sup id="cite_ref-Long_2001.2C_p._51_45-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Long_2001.2C_p._51-45">[45]</a></sup> By 1992, the LS 400's base price had risen 18 percent.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1993, Lexus launched the mid-size <a href="/wiki/Lexus_GS" title="Lexus GS">GS 300</a> sports sedan, based on the Toyota Aristo using the <a href="/wiki/List_of_Toyota_platforms#S" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Toyota platforms">Toyota "S" platform</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Crown_(S140)" class="mw-redirect" title="Toyota Crown (S140)">Toyota Crown</a>, which had sold for two years prior in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-dw141_41-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dw141-41">[41]</a></sup> The GS 300 was priced below the LS 400 in the marque's lineup.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup> That same year, Lexus became one of the first marques to debut a <a href="/wiki/Certified_pre-owned" class="mw-redirect" title="Certified pre-owned">certified pre-owned</a> program, with the aim of improving trade-in model values.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[49]</a></sup> The marque introduced the second generation LS 400 in 1994.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup> In May 1995, sales were threatened by the U.S. government's proposal of 100 percent <a href="/wiki/Tariff" title="Tariff">tariffs</a> on upscale Japanese cars in response to the widening U.S.-Japan <a href="/wiki/Trade_deficit" class="mw-redirect" title="Trade deficit">trade deficit</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-tar_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tar-51">[51]</a></sup> SUVs were exempt from the proposed sanctions.<sup id="cite_ref-d160_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d160-52">[52]</a></sup> Normal sales operations resumed by late 1995 when the Japanese auto manufacturers collectively agreed to greater American investments and the tariffs were not enacted.<sup id="cite_ref-tar_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tar-51">[51]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_(MCV20R)_LXS_sedan_(2011-10-25)_01a.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a sedan." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg/220px-1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg" width="220" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg/330px-1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg/440px-1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_%28MCV20R%29_LXS_sedan_%282011-10-25%29_01a.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3749" data-file-height="2181" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:1996-1999_Lexus_ES_300_(MCV20R)_LXS_sedan_(2011-10-25)_01a.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Lexus_ES#XV20" title="Lexus ES">ES 300</a> was the best-selling Lexus sedan in the 1990s</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1996, Lexus debuted its first sport utility vehicle, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LX" title="Lexus LX">LX 450</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">[53]</a></sup> followed by the third generation ES 300 sedan. The marque's plans for developing an SUV model had accelerated during the U.S.-Japan tariff discussions of 1995.<sup id="cite_ref-d160_52-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d160-52">[52]</a></sup> Lexus added the first luxury-branded <a href="/wiki/Crossover_SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="Crossover SUV">crossover SUV</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX" title="Lexus RX">RX 300</a>, and the second generation GS 300 and GS 400 sedans in 1998. The RX crossover targeted <a href="/wiki/Suburban" class="mw-redirect" title="Suburban">suburban</a> buyers who desired an upmarket SUV but did not need the LX's off-road capability.<sup id="cite_ref-d172_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d172-54">[54]</a></sup> It was particularly successful, eventually becoming the marque's top-selling model ahead of the ES sedan.<sup id="cite_ref-d172_54-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d172-54">[54]</a></sup> The same year, Lexus made its debut in South America's most populous country when it launched sales in Brazil.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">[55]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[56]</a></sup> In 1999, Lexus recorded its 1 millionth vehicle sold in the U.S. market<sup id="cite_ref-msntl_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msntl-44">[44]</a></sup> and was ranked the top-selling premium car maker in the U.S. overall.<sup id="cite_ref-d172_54-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d172-54">[54]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2000s:_Global_reorganization">2000s: Global reorganization</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: 2000s: Global reorganization">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of an SUV parked next to a beach." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG/220px-Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG" width="220" height="130" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG/330px-Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG/440px-Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2166" data-file-height="1275" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_RX_400h_front.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2004 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX_(XU30)" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus RX (XU30)">RX 400h</a>, first hybrid version of Lexus' best-selling vehicle</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2000, Lexus introduced the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_IS" title="Lexus IS">IS</a> line, a series of entry-level sport sedans. In 2001, the first convertible was introduced, as well as the SC 430, a redesigned ES 300 and the third generation LS 430.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[57]</a></sup> The GX 470 mid-size SUV debuted in 2002, followed by the second generation RX 330 in 2003.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[58]</a></sup> The following year, Lexus recorded its 2 millionth U.S. vehicle sale,<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">[59]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[60]</a></sup> and the first luxury-branded production hybrid SUV, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX_(XU30)" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus RX (XU30)">RX 400h</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-hy_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hy-61">[61]</a></sup> This vehicle used Toyota's <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_Synergy_Drive" title="Hybrid Synergy Drive">Hybrid Synergy Drive</a> system that combined gasoline and electric motors.<sup id="cite_ref-hyh_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hyh-62">[62]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2005, Lexus completed an organizational separation from parent company Toyota,<sup id="cite_ref-lown_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lown-63">[63]</a></sup> with dedicated design, engineering, training, and manufacturing centers working exclusively for the division.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">[64]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ain_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ain-65">[65]</a></sup> This effort coincided with Lexus' launch in its home market of Japan and an expanded global launch of the brand in markets such as China.<sup id="cite_ref-ain_65-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ain-65">[65]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">[66]</a></sup> Executives aimed to increase Lexus sales outside of its largest market in the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-ain_65-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ain-65">[65]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nk_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nk-67">[67]</a></sup> To accompany this expansion, next generation Lexus vehicles were redesigned as "global models" for international release.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">[68]</a></sup> In the European market, where Lexus had long faced struggling sales owing to low brand recognition, few dedicated dealerships, and 1990s <a href="/wiki/Import_quota" title="Import quota">import quotas</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[69]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">[70]</a></sup> the marque announced plans to introduce hybrid and diesel powertrains,<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[71]</a></sup> increase the number of Lexus dealerships, and expand operations in emerging markets such as Russia.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">[72]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-emerging_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-emerging-73">[73]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a sedan." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg/220px-Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg" width="220" height="120" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg/330px-Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg/440px-Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="979" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_IS250_silver.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2005 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_IS" title="Lexus IS">Lexus IS</a>, second generation with F marque variant in 2007</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus' arrival in the Japanese market in July 2005 marked the first introduction of a Japanese premium car marque in the domestic market.<sup id="cite_ref-cbs_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbs-3">[3]</a></sup> New generation LS, IS, ES, GS, and RX models subsequently became available in Japan along with the SC 430, ending domestic sales of Toyota-branded models under the Celsior, Altezza, Windom, Aristo, Harrier, and Soarer nameplates, respectively. The Altezza and Aristo were previously exclusive to Japanese Toyota retail sales channels called <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Vista_Store" class="mw-redirect" title="Toyota Vista Store">Toyota Vista Store</a>, the Windom was exclusive to Toyota Corolla Store, the Celsior and Harrier were exclusive to Toyopet Store, and the Soarer was previously available at both Toyota Store and Toyopet Store locations.<sup id="cite_ref-d193_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d193-74">[74]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nihon_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nihon-75">[75]</a></sup> Lexus models sold in Japan featured higher specifications and a price premium compared with their discontinued Toyota counterparts.<sup id="cite_ref-d193_74-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d193-74">[74]</a></sup> Sales for the first half-year were slower than expected,<sup id="cite_ref-LexJP_76-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LexJP-76">[76]</a></sup> affected by the contraction of the domestic auto market and price increases,<sup id="cite_ref-ljp_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ljp-77">[77]</a></sup> but improved in subsequent months with an expanded lineup.<sup id="cite_ref-ljp_77-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ljp-77">[77]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[78]</a></sup></p>
<p>Through the mid-2000s, Lexus experienced sales successes in South Korea and Taiwan, becoming the top-selling import make in both markets in 2005;<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[79]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">[80]</a></sup> the marque also sold well in the Middle East, where it ranked first or second among rivals in multiple countries,<sup id="cite_ref-furutani_81-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-furutani-81">[81]</a></sup> and in Australia, where Lexus reached third in luxury car sales in 2006.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">[82]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">[83]</a></sup> Division executives in 2006 announced an expansion goal from 68 countries to 76 worldwide by 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-lexglobal_84-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lexglobal-84">[84]</a></sup> By the end of the decade, this expansion resulted in official launches in Malaysia and South Africa in 2006,<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">[85]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-za_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-za-86">[86]</a></sup> Indonesia in 2007,<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">[87]</a></sup> Chile in 2008,<sup id="cite_ref-chile_88-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-chile-88">[88]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-LexusChile_89-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LexusChile-89">[89]</a></sup> and the Philippines in 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-lexusmanila_90-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lexusmanila-90">[90]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Hybrids_and_F_models">Hybrids and F models</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Hybrids and F models">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In 2006, Lexus began sales of the <a href="/wiki/GS_450h" class="mw-redirect" title="GS 450h">GS 450h</a>, a <a href="/wiki/V6_engine" title="V6 engine">V6</a> hybrid performance sedan,<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">[91]</a></sup> and launched the fourth generation <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS#Fourth_generation_.28USF40.2FUSF41.29" title="Lexus LS">LS line</a>, comprising both standard- and long-<a href="/wiki/Wheelbase" title="Wheelbase">wheelbase</a> V8 (LS 460 and LS 460 L) and hybrid (LS 600h and LS 600h L) versions.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">[92]</a></sup> The fifth generation ES 350 also debuted in the same year. The LS 600h L subsequently went on sale as the most expensive sedan ever produced in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-ult_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ult-93">[93]</a></sup> By the end of 2006, Lexus' annual sales had reached 475,000 vehicles worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-global_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-global-94">[94]</a></sup> In January 2007, Lexus announced a new <a href="/wiki/Lexus#F_marque" title="Lexus">F marque</a> performance division, which would produce racing-inspired versions of its performance models. The IS F, made its debut at the 2007 North American International Auto Show,<sup id="cite_ref-F_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-F-95">[95]</a></sup> accompanied by a concept car, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LF" title="Lexus LF">LF-A</a>.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a sedan." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg/220px-Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg" width="220" height="139" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg/330px-Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg/440px-Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1310" data-file-height="828" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Tino_Rossini%27s_Reviews_-_025_-_2010_Lexus_GS450h.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2006 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_GS_(S190)" title="Lexus GS (S190)">GS 450h</a>, first rear-wheel drive hybrid</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In October 2007, Lexus entered the <a href="/wiki/SEMA" title="SEMA">Specialty Equipment Market Association</a> show in the U.S. for the first time with the IS F, and announced its <a href="/wiki/Lexus_F#F_Sport" title="Lexus F">F-Sport</a> performance trim level and factory-sanctioned accessory line.<sup id="cite_ref-Ramsey_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ramsey-96">[96]</a></sup> Increased emphasis on sporty models was an effort to target rivals from Mercedes-Benz's <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG" title="Mercedes-AMG">AMG</a> and BMW's <a href="/wiki/BMW_M" title="BMW M">M</a> divisions.<sup id="cite_ref-F_95-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-F-95">[95]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">[97]</a></sup> Models such as the SC 400 and GS 400 had received favorable reactions from sport luxury buyers,<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">[98]</a></sup> most Lexus models had been characterized as favoring comfort over sporty road feel and handling, compared with European rivals.<sup id="cite_ref-motorweek_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-motorweek-99">[99]</a></sup> By the end of 2007, Lexus annual worldwide sales had surpassed 500,000 vehicles,<sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">[100]</a></sup> and the marque ranked as the top-selling premium import in China for the first time.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">[101]</a></sup> The largest sales markets in order of size for 2007 were the U.S., Japan, the UK, China, Canada, and Russia.<sup id="cite_ref-global_94-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-global-94">[94]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-07s_102-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-07s-102">[102]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2008, amidst the <a href="/wiki/Late-2000s_recession" class="mw-redirect" title="Late-2000s recession">late-2000s recession</a> and a weakened world car market, global sales fell 16 percent to 435,000,<sup id="cite_ref-gazoo_103-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gazoo-103">[103]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-luxs_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-luxs-104">[104]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-08l_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-08l-105">[105]</a></sup> with declines in markets such as the U.S. and Europe where deliveries fell by 21 percent and 27.5 percent, respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-08s_106-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-08s-106">[106]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">[107]</a></sup> In 2009, the marque launched the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_HS" title="Lexus HS">HS 250h</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-hs_108-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hs-108">[108]</a></sup> a dedicated hybrid sedan for North America and Japan, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX_(AL10)" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus RX (AL10)">RX 450h</a>, the second generation hybrid SUV replacing the earlier RX 400h, and later that year debuted the <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$375,000</span> production <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LFA" title="Lexus LFA">LFA</a> exotic coupe.<sup id="cite_ref-bwl_109-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bwl-109">[109]</a></sup> In late 2009, citing higher sales of hybrid models over their petrol counterparts,<sup id="cite_ref-ukh_110-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ukh-110">[110]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">[111]</a></sup> Lexus announced plans to become a hybrid-only marque in Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-euh_112-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-euh-112">[112]</a></sup> By the end of the decade, Lexus ranked as the fourth-largest premium car make in the world by volume,<sup id="cite_ref-sales_113-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sales-113">[113]</a></sup> and was the number one selling premium car marque in the U.S. for 10 consecutive years.<sup id="cite_ref-08l_105-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-08l-105">[105]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sales_113-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sales-113">[113]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-09s_114-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-09s-114">[114]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2010s:_Recent_developments">2010s: Recent developments</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: 2010s: Recent developments">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a coupe." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg/220px-Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg" width="220" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg/330px-Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg/440px-Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1975" data-file-height="1148" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LFA_Yellow_Las_Vegas_Speedway.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2012 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LFA" title="Lexus LFA">Lexus LFA</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2010, Lexus underwent a gradual sales recovery in North America and Asia as the marque focused on adding hybrids and new model derivatives.<sup id="cite_ref-furutani_81-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-furutani-81">[81]</a></sup> Sales in the U.S. held steady despite the <a href="/wiki/2009%E2%80%932010_Toyota_vehicle_recalls" class="mw-redirect" title="20092010 Toyota vehicle recalls">20092010 Toyota vehicle recalls</a>, several of which included Lexus models.<sup id="cite_ref-nyt_115-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-115">[115]</a></sup> The ES 350 and certain IS models were affected by a recall for potentially jamming <a href="/wiki/2009%E2%80%932010_Toyota_vehicle_recalls#Floor_mat_recall" class="mw-redirect" title="20092010 Toyota vehicle recalls">floor mats</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-nyt_115-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-115">[115]</a></sup> while parent company Toyota bore the brunt of negative publicity amid investigations over its series of product recalls and problem rates per-vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-nyt_115-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-115">[115]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-uia_116-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-uia-116">[116]</a></sup> The redesigned <a href="/wiki/Lexus_GX#Second_generation_.282009-present.29" title="Lexus GX">GX 460</a> was also voluntarily recalled in April 2010 for a <a href="/wiki/Patch_(computing)" title="Patch (computing)">software update</a>, one week after <i><a href="/wiki/Consumer_Reports" title="Consumer Reports">Consumer Reports</a></i> issued a recommendation not to buy the SUV, citing a possible rollover risk following the slow <a href="/wiki/Electronic_stability_control" title="Electronic stability control">stability control</a> response to a high-speed emergency turn.<sup id="cite_ref-ngx_117-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ngx-117">[117]</a></sup> Although the publication knew of no reported incidents, the GX 460 received updated stability control software.<sup id="cite_ref-ngx_117-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ngx-117">[117]</a></sup></p>
<p>In late 2010 and early 2011, Lexus began sales of the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_CT" title="Lexus CT">CT 200h</a>, a compact four-door hybrid <a href="/wiki/Hatchback" title="Hatchback">hatchback</a> designed for Europe, in multiple markets.<sup id="cite_ref-ct_118-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ct-118">[118]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">[119]</a></sup> Sales of lower-displacement regional models were also expanded, beginning with the ES 240 in China followed by the RX 270; Japan, Russia, and Taiwan were among markets which received model variants intended for reduced emissions or import taxes.<sup id="cite_ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120">[120]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">[121]</a></sup> In March 2011, the <a href="/wiki/2011_T%C5%8Dhoku_earthquake_and_tsunami" title="2011 Thoku earthquake and tsunami">Thoku earthquake and tsunami</a> caused severe disruption to Lexus' Japan-based production lines, hindering the marque's near-term sales prospects.<sup id="cite_ref-qk_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qk-122">[122]</a></sup> Lexus' U.S. executives stated that due to vehicle shortages amidst close competition from BMW, Mercedes-Benz, and <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a>, the marque would not remain the country's top-selling premium car brand.<sup id="cite_ref-qk_122-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qk-122">[122]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Front quarter view of a hatchback." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg/220px-Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg" width="220" height="128" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg/330px-Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg/440px-Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2632" data-file-height="1529" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_CT_200h_Japan_2011_front.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2010 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_CT" title="Lexus CT">CT 200h</a>, first Lexus hatchback</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Cumulative sales results for 2011 indicated a 14 percent sales drop in the U.S. market,<sup id="cite_ref-us11_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-us11-123">[123]</a></sup> along with sales increases of 40 percent and 27 percent in Europe and Japan respectively,<sup id="cite_ref-eu11_124-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-eu11-124">[124]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-jp11_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jp11-125">[125]</a></sup> for a global sales total of 410,000 units.<sup id="cite_ref-asiapac_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-asiapac-126">[126]</a></sup> Lexus' streak of 11 consecutive years as the best-selling luxury marque in the U.S. ended that year, with the title going to BMW followed by Mercedes-Benz.<sup id="cite_ref-predator_127-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-predator-127">[127]</a></sup> While 45 percent of Lexus sales in the U.S. in 2011 relied upon the RX luxury crossover SUV, rival Mercedes-Benz's best-selling offering was the E-Class mid-luxury sedan, which commands considerably higher prices.<sup id="cite_ref-big_picture_128-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-big_picture-128">[128]</a></sup> Subsequently, Toyota chairman <a href="/wiki/Akio_Toyoda" title="Akio Toyoda">Akio Toyoda</a> vowed to restore passion to the marque and further increase its organizational independence, admitting that "...back then we did not regard Lexus as a brand, but as a distribution channel". As a result of Toyoda's organizational changes, Lexus senior managers report directly to the chairman for the first time in the marque's history.<sup id="cite_ref-predator_127-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-predator-127">[127]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-big_picture_128-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-big_picture-128">[128]</a></sup></p>
<p>In January 2012, the marque began sales of the fourth generation GS line, including GS 350 and GS 450h variants, as well as a lower-displacement GS 250 model for select markets.<sup id="cite_ref-129" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129">[129]</a></sup> In April 2012, the sixth generation ES line, include ES 350 and ES 300h variants, debuted at the <a href="/wiki/New_York_International_Auto_Show" title="New York International Auto Show">New York International Auto Show</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2013es_130-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2013es-130">[130]</a></sup></p>
<p>In April 2014, Lexus unveiled the five-seater NX crossover. The vehicle features a very first for a Lexus vehicle: a turbocharger. Its nomenclature is denoted as the 200t. In August 2014, Toyota announced it would be cutting its Lexus spare parts prices in China by up to 35 percent. The company admitted the move was in response to a probe foreshadowed earlier in the month by China's <a href="/wiki/National_Development_and_Reform_Commission" title="National Development and Reform Commission">National Development and Reform Commission</a> of Lexus spare parts policies, as part of an industry-wide investigation into what the Chinese regulator considers exorbitantly high prices being charged by automakers for spare parts and after-sales servicing.<sup id="cite_ref-ToyotaChina_131-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ToyotaChina-131">[131]</a></sup></p>
<p>In March 2016, Lexus announced that it will be producing a new flagship vehicle: the two-door LC 500. The vehicle will be produced for late 2017 in a V8 version putting out 467 horsepower. The LC 500h, a V6 hybrid variant, could potentially become available in late 2017 or early 2018.</p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Operations">Operations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Operations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Lexus International, headed by managing officer Tokuo Fukuichi, coordinates the worldwide operations of Toyota's luxury division.<sup id="cite_ref-exec_135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-exec-135">[135]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-seek_136-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-seek-136">[136]</a></sup> Other executives at Lexus' global headquarters, located in <a href="/wiki/Nagoya" title="Nagoya">Nagoya</a>, Aichi,<sup id="cite_ref-nagoya_137-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nagoya-137">[137]</a></sup> include Mark Templin, executive vice president of Lexus International,<sup id="cite_ref-exec_135-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-exec-135">[135]</a></sup> and managers of the marque's Japan Sales and Marketing and global Product and Marketing Planning divisions.<sup id="cite_ref-seek_136-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-seek-136">[136]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">[138]</a></sup> While organizationally separate from its parent company, Lexus International reports directly to Toyota chief executive officer Akio Toyoda.<sup id="cite_ref-asiapac_126-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-asiapac-126">[126]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the U.S., Lexus operations are headed by Jeffrey Bracken, group vice president and general manager of the U.S. Lexus division, located in <a href="/wiki/Southern_California" title="Southern California">Southern California</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-lexusus_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lexusus-139">[139]</a></sup> In Europe, Lexus operations are headed by Alain Uyttenhoven, vice president of Lexus Europe, located in Brussels.<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">[140]</a></sup> Companion design facilities are located in Southern California<sup id="cite_ref-141" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-141">[141]</a></sup> and central Japan,<sup id="cite_ref-ctr_142-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctr-142">[142]</a></sup> with the head design studio devoted entirely to Lexus models in Toyota City, Aichi.<sup id="cite_ref-ctr_142-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ctr-142">[142]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">[143]</a></sup></p>
<p>Lexus sales operations vary in structure by region. In many markets, such as the U.S., the dealership network is a distinct organization from corporate headquarters,<sup id="cite_ref-qk_122-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qk-122">[122]</a></sup> with separately owned and operated Lexus <a href="/wiki/Showroom" title="Showroom">showrooms</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">[144]</a></sup> By contrast, in Japan all 143 dealerships in the country are owned and operated by Lexus.<sup id="cite_ref-ljp_77-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ljp-77">[77]</a></sup> Several markets have a designated, third party <a href="/wiki/Distribution_(business)" title="Distribution (business)">regional distributor</a>; for example, in the United Arab Emirates, sales operations are managed by Al-Futtaim Motors LLC,<sup id="cite_ref-furutani_81-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-furutani-81">[81]</a></sup> and in Costa Rica, Lexus vehicles are sold via regional distributor Purdy Motors S.A.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">[145]</a></sup> Other officially sanctioned regional distributors have sold Lexus models prior to the launch of, or in absence of, a dedicated dealership network.<sup id="cite_ref-za_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-za-86">[86]</a></sup></p>
<p>The Lexus brand will be launching in the Indian market in 2017,<sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146">[146]</a></sup> with the models <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX450h" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus RX450h">RX450h</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LX450" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus LX450">LX450d</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LX570" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus LX570">LX570d</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lexus_ES300" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus ES300">ES300h</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-autocarindia.com_147-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autocarindia.com-147">[147]</a></sup> Dealerships in <a href="/wiki/Mumbai" title="Mumbai">Mumbai</a>, <a href="/wiki/Delhi" title="Delhi">Delhi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gurgaon" title="Gurgaon">Gurgaon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bengaluru" class="mw-redirect" title="Bengaluru">Bengaluru</a> will be operational by March 2017 when the brand begins sales in India.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Precise_language" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The text near this tag is dated.">needs update</span></a></i>]</sup> A second set of dealerships will be in <a href="/wiki/Chandigarh" title="Chandigarh">Chandigarh</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cochin" class="mw-redirect" title="Cochin">Cochin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chennai" title="Chennai">Chennai</a> and will be operational toward the end of 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-autocarindia.com_147-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autocarindia.com-147">[147]</a></sup> This will make Lexus the fifth luxury brand to be launched in India after <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_India" title="Mercedes-Benz India">Mercedes-Benz</a>, <a href="/wiki/Porsche_India" title="Porsche India">Porsche</a>, <a href="/wiki/BMW_India" title="BMW India">BMW</a> and <a href="/wiki/Audi_India" title="Audi India">Audi</a> respectively.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sales">Sales</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Sales">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Global sales of Lexus vehicles reached an all-time high in 2007, with a total of 518,000. Sales decreased in subsequent years due to the effects of the 2008 recession and the Japanese tsunami of 2011. Following this, sales recovered and reached a new high of 523,000 in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">[148]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2014, the Lexus brand set a new global sales record after selling 582,000 vehicles. This made Lexus the fourth best selling luxury brand in the world, trailing BMW, Audi and Mercedes-Benz.<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">[149]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_College1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Rectangular windowed building, with landscaping and a sign in front labeled 'Lexus'." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Lexus_College1.jpg/220px-Lexus_College1.jpg" width="220" height="91" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Lexus_College1.jpg/330px-Lexus_College1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Lexus_College1.jpg/440px-Lexus_College1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="530" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_College1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Fuji Lexus College, training facility for dealers in <a href="/wiki/Shizuoka_Prefecture" title="Shizuoka Prefecture">Shizuoka</a>, Japan</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Global sales of Lexus vehicles increased by 12 percent in 2015 to reach another annual sales record with 652,00 units sold worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">[150]</a></sup></p>
<p>Global cumulative sales of Lexus brand <a href="/wiki/Hybrid_electric_vehicle" title="Hybrid electric vehicle">hybrid electric cars</a> reached the 500,000 mark in November 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-TMC5miHEVs_151-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TMC5miHEVs-151">[151]</a></sup> The 1&#160;million sales milestone was achieved in March 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-Lexus1mi_152-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lexus1mi-152">[152]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RX" title="Lexus RX">Lexus RX 400h/RX 450h</a> ranks as the top selling Lexus hybrid with 335,000 units delivered worldwide as of March 2016<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, followed by the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_CT" title="Lexus CT">Lexus CT 200h</a> with 267,000 units.<sup id="cite_ref-Lexus1mi_152-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lexus1mi-152">[152]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Financial_performance">Financial performance</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Financial performance">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Financial data of Lexus operations are not disclosed publicly.<sup id="cite_ref-amplify_153-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-amplify-153">[153]</a></sup> However, automotive analysts estimate that the Lexus division contributes a disproportionate share of Toyota's profits, relative to its limited production and sales volume.<sup id="cite_ref-amplify_153-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-amplify-153">[153]</a></sup> Interviews with retired division officials indicate that depending on sales volume, vehicle <a href="/wiki/Product_development" class="mw-redirect" title="Product development">product development</a> cycles, and <a href="/wiki/Exchange_rate" title="Exchange rate">exchange rates</a>, Lexus sales have accounted for as much as half of Toyota's annual U.S. profit in certain years.<sup id="cite_ref-amplify_153-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-amplify-153">[153]</a></sup> Division executives have employed pricing strategies aimed at sustaining <a href="/wiki/Profit_margin" title="Profit margin">profit margins</a> rather than sales volume, with historically fewer price <a href="/wiki/Incentive" title="Incentive">incentives</a> than rival brands.<sup id="cite_ref-amplify_153-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-amplify-153">[153]</a></sup> In 2006, Lexus entered <a href="/wiki/Interbrand" title="Interbrand">Interbrand</a>'s list of the <a href="/wiki/BrandZ" title="BrandZ">Top 100 Global Brands</a> for the first time, with an estimated <a href="/wiki/Brand_equity#Measurement" title="Brand equity">brand value</a> of approximately $3 billion annually.<sup id="cite_ref-154" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-154">[154]</a></sup> In 2009, Interbrand ranked Lexus as Japan's seventh largest brand, between <a href="/wiki/Panasonic" title="Panasonic">Panasonic</a> and Nissan, based on revenue, earnings, and market value.<sup id="cite_ref-jbrand_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jbrand-2">[2]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Automobiles">Automobiles</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Automobiles">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Vehicle_lineup">Vehicle lineup</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Vehicle lineup">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Further information: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Lexus_vehicles" title="List of Lexus vehicles">List of Lexus vehicles</a></div>
<p>The global Lexus lineup features sedans of different size classes, including the <a href="/wiki/Compact_executive_car" title="Compact executive car">compact</a> IS and HS models, <a href="/wiki/Mid-size_car" title="Mid-size car">mid-size</a> ES and GS models, and the <a href="/wiki/Full-size_car" title="Full-size car">full-size</a> LS. Convertibles include the IS C models. Sport-utility vehicles range in size from the compact NX and RX crossover, to the mid-size GX and the full-size LX. Hybrid models include the CT hatchback, HS sedan, and variants of the GS, LS, and RX.<sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup> The F marque line produces a variant of the GS sedan, the RC coupe and the LFA.<sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="F_marque">F marque</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: F marque">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Lexus_F" title="Lexus F">Lexus F</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lexus_F#F_Sport" title="Lexus F">Lexus F-Sport</a></div>
