</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus produces its highest-performance models under its F marque division.<sup id="cite_ref-F_95-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-F-95">[95]</a></sup> The name refers to Flagship and <a href="/wiki/Fuji_Speedway" title="Fuji Speedway">Fuji Speedway</a> in Japan, whose first corner, 27R, inspired the shape of the "<i>F</i>" emblem.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">[156]</a></sup> F marque models are developed by the Lexus Vehicle Performance Development Division.<sup id="cite_ref-157" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-157">[157]</a></sup> The first F marque model, the IS F, went on sale in 2007, followed by the LFA in 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-bwl_109-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bwl-109">[109]</a></sup> A related <a href="/wiki/Lexus_F#F_Sport" title="Lexus F">F-Sport</a> performance trim level and factory-sanctioned accessory line is available for standard Lexus models such as the IS 250 and IS 350.<sup id="cite_ref-Ramsey_96-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ramsey-96">[96]</a></sup> F-Sport succeeded an earlier in-house tuning effort, the <a href="/wiki/Toyota_Racing_Development" title="Toyota Racing Development">TRD</a>-based L-Tuned, which had offered performance packages on the IS and GS sedans in the early 2000s (decade).<sup id="cite_ref-158" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-158">[158]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-159" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-159">[159]</a></sup></p>
<p>The latest editions to the performance F marque include the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RC" title="Lexus RC">Lexus RC</a> F and <a href="/wiki/Lexus_GS" title="Lexus GS">Lexus GS</a> F.<sup id="cite_ref-160" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-160">[160]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Model_nomenclature">Model nomenclature</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Model nomenclature">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Lexus production models are named <a href="/wiki/Alphanumeric" title="Alphanumeric">alphanumerically</a> using two-letter designations followed by three digits. The first letter indicates relative status in the Lexus model range (<a href="/wiki/Ranking" title="Ranking">ranking</a>),<sup id="cite_ref-lnam_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lnam-161">[161]</a></sup> and the second letter refers to <a href="/wiki/Car_body_style" class="mw-redirect" title="Car body style">car body style</a> or type<sup id="cite_ref-lnam_161-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lnam-161">[161]</a></sup> (e.g. LS for 'luxury sedan'). The three digits indicate <a href="/wiki/Engine_displacement" title="Engine displacement">engine displacement</a> in liters multiplied by a factor of one hundred (e.g. 350 for a 3.5 L engine).<sup id="cite_ref-lnam_161-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lnam-161">[161]</a></sup> A space is used between the letters and numbers. The same letter may be used differently depending on the model; 'S' can refer to 'sedan'<sup id="cite_ref-lnam_161-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lnam-161">[161]</a></sup> or 'sport'<sup id="cite_ref-nihon_75-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nihon-75">[75]</a></sup> (e.g. in LS and SC), while 'X' refers to '<a href="/wiki/Sport_utility_vehicle" title="Sport utility vehicle">luxury utility vehicle</a>' or SUV.<sup id="cite_ref-lnam_161-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lnam-161">[161]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-162" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-162">[162]</a></sup> On hybrids, the three digits refer to the combined gasoline-electric output.<sup id="cite_ref-hyh_62-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hyh-62">[62]</a></sup> For certain models, a <a href="/wiki/Lower_case" class="mw-redirect" title="Lower case">lower case</a> letter placed after the alphanumeric designation indicates powerplant type ('h' for hybrid, 'd' for diesel, 't' for turbocharged),<sup id="cite_ref-ukh_110-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ukh-110">[110]</a></sup> while <a href="/wiki/Capital_letter" class="mw-redirect" title="Capital letter">capital letter</a>(s) placed at the end indicates a class subtype (e.g. 'L' for long-wheelbase,<sup id="cite_ref-lown_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lown-63">[63]</a></sup> 'C' for coupe, 'AWD' for <a href="/wiki/All-wheel_drive" title="All-wheel drive">all-wheel drive</a>). On F marque models, the two-letter designation and the letter 'F' are used with no numbers or hyphens (e.g. IS F).<sup id="cite_ref-ukh_110-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ukh-110">[110]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Design_and_technology">Design and technology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Design and technology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Palmrest with forward buttons and movable control knob." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg/220px-Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg" width="220" height="157" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg/330px-Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg/440px-Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="570" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Remote_Touch_lexus_controller.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lexus <a href="/wiki/Remote_Touch" title="Remote Touch">Remote Touch</a> controller</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus design has traditionally placed an emphasis on targeting specific vehicle development standards.<sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-163">[163]</a></sup> Since the marque's inception, design targets have ranged from aerodynamics and <a href="/wiki/Ride_quality" title="Ride quality">ride quality</a> to interior ergonomics.<sup id="cite_ref-d68_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d68-31">[31]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">[164]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Backronym" title="Backronym">backronym</a> "IDEAL" ("Impressive, Dynamic, Elegant, Advanced, and Lasting") is used in the development process.<sup id="cite_ref-165" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">[165]</a></sup> Each vehicle is designed according to approximately 500 specific product standards, known as "Lexus Musts," on criteria such as <a href="/wiki/Leather" title="Leather">leather</a> seat stitching.<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">[166]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-webcg_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-webcg-167">[167]</a></sup> Design elements from the marque's concept vehicle line, the <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LF" title="Lexus LF">LF series</a> (including the 2003 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LF-S" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus LF-S">LF-S</a> and 2004 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LF-C" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexus LF-C">LF-C</a>), have been incorporated in production models.<sup id="cite_ref-168" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-168">[168]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">[169]</a></sup></p>
<p>Vehicle cabins have incorporated <a href="/wiki/Electroluminescence" title="Electroluminescence">electroluminescent</a> Optitron gauges,<sup id="cite_ref-d71_170-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d71-170">[170]</a></sup> SmartAccess, a <a href="/wiki/Advanced_key" class="mw-redirect" title="Advanced key">smart key</a> entry and startup system,<sup id="cite_ref-tech_171-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tech-171">[171]</a></sup> and multimedia features. Beginning with the 2010 RX and HS models, the <a href="/wiki/Remote_Touch" title="Remote Touch">Remote Touch</a> system, featuring a <a href="/wiki/Computer_mouse" title="Computer mouse">computer mouse</a>-like controller with <a href="/wiki/Haptic_technology" title="Haptic technology">haptic feedback</a>, was introduced;<sup id="cite_ref-hs_108-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hs-108">[108]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-172" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-172">[172]</a></sup> other models have featured <a href="/wiki/Touchscreen" title="Touchscreen">touchscreen</a> controls (through the 2009 model year) as a navigation screen interface.<sup id="cite_ref-tech_171-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tech-171">[171]</a></sup> 2014 saw the introduction of the next version of Lexus remote-touch innovationsthe Remote Touch Interface Touchpad in the new <a href="/wiki/Lexus_RC" title="Lexus RC">RC Coupe</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-173" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-173">[173]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1989, Lexus became among the first premium car marques to equip models with premium audio systems, in partnership with stereo firm <a href="/wiki/Nakamichi" title="Nakamichi">Nakamichi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-174" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-174">[174]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-caud_175-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-caud-175">[175]</a></sup> Since 2001, optional <a href="/wiki/Surround_sound" title="Surround sound">surround sound</a> systems are offered via <a href="/wiki/High-end_audio" title="High-end audio">high-end audio</a> purveyor <a href="/wiki/Mark_Levinson_Audio_Systems" title="Mark Levinson Audio Systems">Mark Levinson</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-caud_175-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-caud-175">[175]</a></sup> For reduced cabin noise, the first LS 400 introduced sandwich <a href="/wiki/Steel" title="Steel">steel</a> plating,<sup id="cite_ref-d71_170-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d71-170">[170]</a></sup> and later models added <a href="/wiki/Insulated_glazing#Acoustic_insulating_properties" title="Insulated glazing">acoustic glass</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-176" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-176">[176]</a></sup> In 2006, the LS 460 debuted the first ceiling <a href="/wiki/Air_diffuser" class="mw-redirect" title="Air diffuser">air diffusers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Infrared" title="Infrared">infrared</a> body temperature sensors in a car.<sup id="cite_ref-sae_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sae-177">[177]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-wcoty_178-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wcoty-178">[178]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Telematics" title="Telematics">Telematics</a> services include <a href="/wiki/G-Book" title="G-Book">G-Book</a> with <a href="/wiki/G-Book#G-Link" title="G-Book">G-Link</a> in Asia and <a href="/wiki/Safety_Connect" title="Safety Connect">Lexus Enform</a> in North America.<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">[179]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG" class="image"><img alt="Cutaway car transmission, with exposed gears and internal machinery." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG/220px-Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG/330px-Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG/440px-Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_IS_F_08.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Eight-speed automatic transmission in the IS F and <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS_(XF40)#Refresh" title="Lexus LS (XF40)">LS 460 Sport</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 2006, Lexus incorporated the first production eight-speed <a href="/wiki/Automatic_transmission" title="Automatic transmission">automatic transmission</a> in an automobile with the LS 460,<sup id="cite_ref-sae_177-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sae-177">[177]</a></sup> and the gearbox was later adapted for the GS 460 and IS F models. <a href="/wiki/Continuously_variable_transmission" title="Continuously variable transmission">Continuously variable transmissions</a>, <a href="/wiki/Regenerative_brake" title="Regenerative brake">regenerative brakes</a>, and electric motors have been used on all Lexus hybrid models.<sup id="cite_ref-hyh_62-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hyh-62">[62]</a></sup> In 2007, Lexus executives signaled intentions to equip further models with hybrid powertrains,<sup id="cite_ref-ukh_110-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ukh-110">[110]</a></sup> catering to demands for a decrease in both <a href="/wiki/Pollution" title="Pollution">carbon pollution</a> and <a href="/wiki/Oil_depletion" title="Oil depletion">oil reliance</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ph_180-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ph-180">[180]</a></sup> Hybrid models have been differentiated by separate badging and lighting technology; in 2008, the LS 600h L became the first production vehicle to use <a href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" title="Light-emitting diode">LED</a> <a href="/wiki/LED_headlamp" class="mw-redirect" title="LED headlamp">headlamps</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-181" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-181">[181]</a></sup></p>
<p>Safety features on Lexus models range from stability and handling programs (<a href="/wiki/Electronic_stability_control" title="Electronic stability control">Vehicle Stability Control</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vehicle_Dynamics_Integrated_Management" title="Vehicle Dynamics Integrated Management">Vehicle Dynamics Integrated Management</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-safety_182-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-safety-182">[182]</a></sup> to backup cameras, swivel headlights, and sonar warning systems. The <a href="/wiki/Precrash_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Precrash system">Lexus Pre-Collision System</a> (PCS) integrates multiple safety systems.<sup id="cite_ref-safety_182-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-safety-182">[182]</a></sup> In 2007, Lexus introduced the first car safety systems with infrared and pedestrian detection capabilities, <a href="/wiki/Lane_departure_warning_system" title="Lane departure warning system">lane keep assist</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Driver_Monitoring_System" title="Driver Monitoring System">Driver Monitoring System</a> with <a href="/wiki/Facial_recognition_system" title="Facial recognition system">facial recognition</a> monitoring of driver attentiveness, and rear pre-collision <a href="/wiki/Whiplash_(medicine)" title="Whiplash (medicine)">whiplash</a> protection, as part of the LS 460 PCS.<sup id="cite_ref-sae_177-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sae-177">[177]</a></sup> As a safety precaution, Lexus <a href="/wiki/Automotive_navigation_system" title="Automotive navigation system">GPS navigation systems</a> in many regions feature a motion lockout when the vehicle reaches a set speed; to prevent distraction, navigation inputs are limited, while voice input and certain buttons are still accessible. This safety feature has attracted criticism because passengers cannot use certain functions when the vehicle is in motion.<sup id="cite_ref-183" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-183">[183]</a></sup> Pre-2007 models came with a hidden manufacturer override option,<sup id="cite_ref-184" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">[184]</a></sup> and updated European models allow operation in motion.<sup id="cite_ref-185" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-185">[185]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Cutaway hybrid car showing electrical connections; auto show display backdrop." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg/220px-Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg" width="220" height="146" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg/330px-Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg/440px-Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3008" data-file-height="2000" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LS_600h_L_powertrain_cutaway.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
2006 <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LS_(XF40)" title="Lexus LS (XF40)">LS 600h</a> and LS 600h L in hybrid form</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Production models in development have included convertibles, crossovers, and dedicated hybrids.<sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">[186]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-wings_187-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wings-187">[187]</a></sup> Under the F marque, Lexus plans to produce high-performance vehicles with its first expressions being the IS F and the LFA. Lexus officials have also discussed standard production model usage of varying <a href="/wiki/Automobile_platform" class="mw-redirect" title="Automobile platform">platforms</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-188" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-188">[188]</a></sup> The LS uses a dedicated platform,<sup id="cite_ref-m31_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m31-28">[28]</a></sup> while the entry-level Lexus ES had been criticized for being too similar to the Toyota Camry, with which it shared platforms until its sixth generation,<sup id="cite_ref-2013es_130-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2013es-130">[130]</a></sup> in both styling and powertrain design.<sup id="cite_ref-189" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">[189]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/N%C3%BCrburgring" title="Nrburgring">Nrburgring</a> test track in Germany has also seen Lexus prototype testing.<sup id="cite_ref-190" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-190">[190]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="L-finesse">L-finesse</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: L-finesse">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LF" title="Lexus LF">Lexus LF</a></div>
<p>Lexus introduced a new <a href="/wiki/Design_language" title="Design language">design language</a> known as "L-finesse" in the mid-2000s with its LF series concepts and the 2006 Lexus GS.<sup id="cite_ref-lfin_191-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lfin-191">[191]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lap_192-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lap-192">[192]</a></sup> L-finesse is represented by three Japanese <a href="/wiki/Kanji" title="Kanji">kanji</a> characters which translate as "Intriguing Elegance, Incisive Simplicity, and Seamless Anticipation".<sup id="cite_ref-lap_192-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lap-192">[192]</a></sup> Design characteristics, including a <a href="/wiki/Fastback" title="Fastback">fastback</a> profile, lower-set <a href="/wiki/Grille" title="Grille">grille</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-own_193-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-own-193">[193]</a></sup> and the use of both convex and concave surfaces,<sup id="cite_ref-own_193-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-own-193">[193]</a></sup> are derived from Japanese cultural motifs (e.g. the phrase <i><a href="/wiki/Kirikaeshi" title="Kirikaeshi">kirikaeshi</a></i> in arrowhead shapes).<sup id="cite_ref-194" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-194">[194]</a></sup> While earlier Lexus models were criticized for reserved and derivative styling, and often mistaken for understated domestic market cars,<sup id="cite_ref-own_193-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-own-193">[193]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Automotive_design" title="Automotive design">automotive design</a> analyses described L-finesse as adding a distinctive nature and embrace of Japanese design identity.<sup id="cite_ref-lfin_191-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lfin-191">[191]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lap_192-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lap-192">[192]</a></sup> Opinions varied for L-finesse's debut on the GS; <i><a href="/wiki/Sports_Car_International" title="Sports Car International">Sports Car International</a>'</i>s analysis praised the vehicle's in-person appearance;<sup id="cite_ref-195" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-195">[195]</a></sup> <i>Automobile Magazine</i> criticized the daring of its forward styling,<sup id="cite_ref-196" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-196">[196]</a></sup> and compared subsequent rival models for design similarities.<sup id="cite_ref-197" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-197">[197]</a></sup> In 2012, the arrival of the redesigned fourth generation Lexus GS featured the introduction of a spindle-shaped grille design, intended to be used on all forthcoming Lexus models.<sup id="cite_ref-nagoya_137-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nagoya-137">[137]</a></sup> L-finesse exhibitions were presented at <a href="/wiki/Milan" title="Milan">Milan</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Salone_del_Mobile" class="mw-redirect" title="Salone del Mobile">Salone del Mobile</a> from 2005 through 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-198" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-198">[198]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Production">Production</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Production">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Assembly_plants">Assembly plants</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Assembly plants">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Car showroom displaying three sedans, the nearest on a glass turntable, in front of a reception counter and windows." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg/220px-Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg/330px-Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg/440px-Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1265" data-file-height="711" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Automobile_Lineup_2007.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lexus models produced by the Tahara plant in <a href="/wiki/Aichi_Prefecture" title="Aichi Prefecture">Aichi</a>, Japan</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The first Lexus vehicles were manufactured in Toyota's <a href="/wiki/Tahara_plant" title="Tahara plant">Tahara plant</a>, a highly sophisticated, computerized manufacturing plant in Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-199">[199]</a></sup> Lexus production techniques include methods and standards of <a href="/wiki/Quality_control" title="Quality control">quality control</a> that differ from Toyota models.<sup id="cite_ref-d88_200-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d88-200">[200]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-201" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-201">[201]</a></sup> At the Tahara plant, separate <a href="/wiki/Assembly_line" title="Assembly line">assembly lines</a> were developed for Lexus vehicles,<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_202-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-202">[202]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-m78_203-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m78-203">[203]</a></sup> along with new molds and specialized manufacturing equipment.<sup id="cite_ref-m78_203-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-m78-203">[203]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Welding" title="Welding">Welding</a> processes, <a href="/wiki/Body_panel" class="mw-redirect" title="Body panel">body panel</a> fit tolerances, and paint quality requirements are more stringent.<sup id="cite_ref-d88_200-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d88-200">[200]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-204" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-204">[204]</a></sup> Lexus plant workers, typically veteran technicians, are identified via repeated performance evaluations and ranked according to skill grade, with limited applicants accepted.<sup id="cite_ref-205" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-205">[205]</a></sup> The highest level <i><a href="/wiki/Takumi" title="Takumi">takumi</a></i> (Japanese for "artisan") engineers are responsible for maintaining production standards at key points in the assembly process, such as testing engine performance.<sup id="cite_ref-lown_63-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lown-63">[63]</a></sup> Production vehicles are given visual inspections for flaws, individually test-driven at high speeds, and subjected to <a href="/wiki/Vibration" title="Vibration">vibration</a> tests.<sup id="cite_ref-d88_200-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d88-200">[200]</a></sup></p>
<p>Through the 2000s (decade), most Lexus sedan and SUV production has occurred in Japan at the Tahara plant in Aichi and Miyata plant in Fukuoka.<sup id="cite_ref-nk_67-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nk-67">[67]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup> In addition to the Tahara factory, Lexus vehicles have been produced at the Miyata plant (Toyota Motor Kyushu, Inc.) in <a href="/wiki/Miyawaka,_Fukuoka" class="mw-redirect" title="Miyawaka, Fukuoka">Miyawaka, Fukuoka</a>, Higashi Fuji plant (Kanto Auto Works, Ltd.) in <a href="/wiki/Susono,_Shizuoka" title="Susono, Shizuoka">Susono, Shizuoka</a>, and Sanage plant (<a href="/wiki/Toyota_Boshoku" title="Toyota Boshoku">Toyota Boshoku Corp.</a>; Araco) in <a href="/wiki/Toyota_City" class="mw-redirect" title="Toyota City">Toyota City</a>, Aichi.<sup id="cite_ref-nk_67-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nk-67">[67]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Front-wheel_drive" title="Front-wheel drive">Front-wheel drive</a> cars, such as the ES and HS, are produced in the <a href="/wiki/Fukuoka_Prefecture" title="Fukuoka Prefecture">Fukuoka Prefecture</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-plant_155-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plant-155">[155]</a></sup> The Kokura plant in <a href="/wiki/Kitakyushu" title="Kitakyushu">Kitakyushu, Fukuoka</a>, which opened in 2008, is a dedicated hybrid production site for Lexus models such as the gasoline-electric RX.<sup id="cite_ref-206" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-206">[206]</a></sup> The North Americanmarket RX 350 (since the 2004 model year) is produced at the Cambridge plant (Toyota Canada, Inc.) in the city of <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Ontario" title="Cambridge, Ontario">Cambridge</a>, in Ontario, Canada, which is the first Lexus production site located outside Japan. In late 2015, Lexus started to assemble North American-spec ES 350 sedans at the Georgetown plant (<a href="/wiki/Toyota_Motor_Manufacturing_Kentucky" title="Toyota Motor Manufacturing Kentucky">TMMK, Inc.</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-207" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-207">[207]</a></sup></p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Quality_rankings">Quality rankings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Quality rankings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In the 2000s (decade), <i><a href="/wiki/Consumer_Reports" title="Consumer Reports">Consumer Reports</a></i> named Lexus among the top five most reliable brands in its Annual Car Reliability Surveys of over one million vehicles across the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-cd06_208-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cd06-208">[208]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-209" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-209">[209]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Service">Service</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Service">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Car showroom with a coupe, two sedans, glass windows, plus large sign reading &quot;Lexus&quot;." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg/220px-Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg" width="220" height="154" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg/330px-Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg/440px-Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1000" data-file-height="700" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_of_Sapporo.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lexus dealership showroom in <a href="/wiki/Sapporo" title="Sapporo">Sapporo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hokkaido" title="Hokkaido">Hokkaido</a>, Japan</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus has become known for efforts to project an upscale image, particularly with service provided after the sale. The waiting areas in service departments are replete with amenities, ranging from refreshment bars to indoor <a href="/wiki/Putting_green" class="mw-redirect" title="Putting green">putting greens</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-210" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-210">[210]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nex_211-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nex-211">[211]</a></sup> Dealerships typically offer complimentary loaner cars or "courtesy cars" and free <a href="/wiki/Car_wash" title="Car wash">car washes</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-nex_211-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nex-211">[211]</a></sup> and some have added on-site cafes and designer boutiques.<sup id="cite_ref-212" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-212">[212]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-213" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-213">[213]</a></sup> Service bays are lined with large <a href="/wiki/Picture_window" class="mw-redirect" title="Picture window">picture windows</a> for owners to watch the servicing of their vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-214" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-214">[214]</a></sup> In 2005, Lexus also began reserving <a href="/wiki/Parking_lot" title="Parking lot">parking lots</a> at major sporting arenas, entertainment events, and shopping malls, with the only requirement for free entry being the ownership of a Lexus vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-215" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-215">[215]</a></sup> An online owner publication, <i>Lexus Magazine</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-216" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-216">[216]</a></sup> features automotive and lifestyle articles and is published online monthly<sup id="cite_ref-217" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-217">[217]</a></sup> and on a mobile site.<sup id="cite_ref-218" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-218">[218]</a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2002, Lexus has scored consecutive top ratings in the <i><a href="/wiki/Auto_Express" title="Auto Express">Auto Express</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-219" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-219">[219]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-220" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-220">[220]</a></sup> and 76,000-respondent <i><a href="/wiki/Top_Gear_(magazine)" title="Top Gear (magazine)">Top Gear</a></i> customer satisfaction surveys in the UK.<sup id="cite_ref-221" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-221">[221]</a></sup> Lexus has also repeatedly topped the 79,000-respondent J.D. Power Customer Service Index<sup id="cite_ref-service_222-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-service-222">[222]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/The_Luxury_Institute" title="The Luxury Institute">Luxury Institute</a>, New York surveys in the U.S.<sup id="cite_ref-223" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-223">[223]</a></sup> As a result of service satisfaction levels, the marque has one of the highest customer loyalty rates in the industry.<sup id="cite_ref-224" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-224">[224]</a></sup> To improve customer service, employees are instructed to follow the "Lexus Covenant," the marque's founding promise (which states that "Lexus will treat each customer as we would a guest in our home"),<sup id="cite_ref-225" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-225">[225]</a></sup> and some dealerships have incorporated training at upscale establishments such as <a href="/wiki/Nordstrom" title="Nordstrom">Nordstrom</a> department stores and <a href="/wiki/Ritz-Carlton" class="mw-redirect" title="Ritz-Carlton">Ritz-Carlton</a> hotels.<sup id="cite_ref-226" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-226">[226]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Motorsport">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Forward view of two racecars on a curved section of racetrack." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg/220px-Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg" width="220" height="134" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg/330px-Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg/440px-Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1487" data-file-height="905" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LFAs_24h-Rennen_N%C3%BCrburgring_2010.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Lexus campaigned at the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_N%C3%BCrburgring" title="24 Hours Nrburgring">24 Hours Nrburgring</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus first entered the motorsport arena in 1999 when its racing unit, Team Lexus,<sup id="cite_ref-227" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-227">[227]</a></sup> fielded two GS 400 race vehicles in the <a href="/wiki/List_of_motorsport_championships#Touring_car" title="List of motorsport championships">Motorola Cup</a> North American Street Stock Championship <a href="/wiki/Touring_car_racing" title="Touring car racing">touring car</a> series. In its 1999 inaugural season, Team Lexus achieved its first victory with its sixth race at <a href="/wiki/Road_Atlanta" title="Road Atlanta">Road Atlanta</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-tlex_228-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tlex-228">[228]</a></sup> Led by <a href="/wiki/Sports_Car_Club_of_America" title="Sports Car Club of America">Sports Car Club of America</a> and <a href="/wiki/International_Motor_Sports_Association" title="International Motor Sports Association">International Motor Sports Association</a> driver Chuck Goldsborough, based in <a href="/wiki/Baltimore,_Maryland" class="mw-redirect" title="Baltimore, Maryland">Baltimore, Maryland</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-lawson_229-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lawson-229">[229]</a></sup> Team Lexus capitalized on the debut of the first generation Lexus IS by entering three IS 300s in the third race of the 2001 <a href="/wiki/Grand-Am_Cup" class="mw-redirect" title="Grand-Am Cup">Grand-Am Cup</a> season at <a href="/wiki/Phoenix,_Arizona" title="Phoenix, Arizona">Phoenix, Arizona</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-va_230-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-va-230">[230]</a></sup> Team Lexus won its first IS 300 victory that year at the <a href="/wiki/Virginia_International_Raceway" title="Virginia International Raceway">Virginia International Raceway</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-va_230-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-va-230">[230]</a></sup> In 2002, Team Lexus' competitive efforts in the Grand-Am Cup ST1 (<a href="/wiki/KONI_Sports_Car_Challenge#Vehicles" class="mw-redirect" title="KONI Sports Car Challenge">Street Tuner</a>) class achieved victories in the Drivers' and Team Championships,<sup id="cite_ref-tlex_228-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tlex-228">[228]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lawson_229-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lawson-229">[229]</a></sup> as well as a sweep of the top three finishes at <a href="/wiki/Circuit_Mont-Tremblant" title="Circuit Mont-Tremblant">Circuit Mont-Tremblant</a> in <a href="/wiki/Quebec" title="Quebec">Quebec</a>, Canada.<sup id="cite_ref-231" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-231">[231]</a></sup></p>
<p>After the release of the Lexus brand in the Japanese domestic market in 2005, Lexus sanctioned the entry of four SC 430 coupes in the <a href="/wiki/Super_GT" title="Super GT">Super GT</a> series of the <a href="/wiki/All_Japan_Grand_Touring_Car_Championship" class="mw-redirect" title="All Japan Grand Touring Car Championship">All Japan Grand Touring Car Championship</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Super_GT#GT500" title="Super GT">GT500</a> class. In the first race of the 2006 series, an SC 430 took the chequered flag,<sup id="cite_ref-232" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-232">[232]</a></sup> and drivers <a href="/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Lotterer" title="Andr Lotterer">Andr Lotterer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Juichi_Wakisaka" title="Juichi Wakisaka">Juichi Wakisaka</a> raced the SC 430 to capture the GT500 championship for that year.<sup id="cite_ref-233" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-233">[233]</a></sup> In 2007, another SC 430 won the GT500 opening round race.<sup id="cite_ref-234" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-234">[234]</a></sup> In 2006, Lexus raced a hybrid vehicle for the first time, entering a GS 450h performance hybrid sedan in partnership with <a href="/wiki/SARD" title="SARD">Sigma Advanced Racing Development</a> at the 24 Hours of Tokachi race in <a href="/wiki/Hokkaido" title="Hokkaido">Hokkaido</a>, Japan.<sup id="cite_ref-235" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-235">[235]</a></sup> Lexus Canada also entered the GS 450h in 2007's <a href="/wiki/Targa_Newfoundland" title="Targa Newfoundland">Targa Newfoundland</a> event.<sup id="cite_ref-236" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-236">[236]</a></sup> In 2009, Lexus Super GT Team SC 430 and IS 350 racers won the GT500 and GT300 championships, respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-237" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-237">[237]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Forward angle view of a racecar on a track; the car is labeled '01', 'Lexus', and 'Telmex'." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg/220px-Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg/330px-Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg/440px-Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1645" data-file-height="929" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_Rolex_24_Racing_Ganassi_racer.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
In 2006, 2007, and 2008, Lexus won the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Daytona" title="24 Hours of Daytona">Rolex Sports Car Series Manufacturers' Championship</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Lexus' participation in <a href="/wiki/Endurance_racing_(motorsport)" title="Endurance racing (motorsport)">endurance racing</a> further includes the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_of_Daytona" title="24 Hours of Daytona">Rolex 24 Hours of Daytona</a>, sanctioned by the <a href="/wiki/Grand_American_Road_Racing_Association" class="mw-redirect" title="Grand American Road Racing Association">Grand American Road Racing Association</a>. After entering the <a href="/wiki/Rolex_Sports_Car_Series" title="Rolex Sports Car Series">Rolex Sports Car Series</a> in 2004, Lexus has won over 15 Rolex Series event races.<sup id="cite_ref-238" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-238">[238]</a></sup> In 2005, Lexus was runner-up, and in 2006, it won the championship.<sup id="cite_ref-239" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-239">[239]</a></sup> Although Toyota has won this race in the past, it was the first time that its luxury arm emerged as the winner. In 2007, six Lexus-powered Daytona prototypes were entered in the Rolex 24 Hours of Daytona event at the <a href="/wiki/Daytona_International_Speedway" title="Daytona International Speedway">Daytona International Speedway</a>. Lexus was a repeat winner of the event, with a Lexus-<a href="/wiki/Riley_Technologies" title="Riley Technologies">Riley</a> prototype driven by <a href="/wiki/Scott_Pruett" title="Scott Pruett">Scott Pruett</a>, <a href="/wiki/Juan_Pablo_Montoya" title="Juan Pablo Montoya">Juan Pablo Montoya</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Salvador_Dur%C3%A1n" title="Salvador Durn">Salvador Durn</a> of <a href="/wiki/Chip_Ganassi_Racing" title="Chip Ganassi Racing">Chip Ganassi Racing</a> finishing first; Lexus-Riley prototypes also took three of the top ten spots.<sup id="cite_ref-240" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-240">[240]</a></sup> In 2008, Lexus won its third consecutive win at Daytona.<sup id="cite_ref-241" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-241">[241]</a></sup> For the <a href="/wiki/2010_Rolex_Sports_Car_Series_season" class="mw-redirect" title="2010 Rolex Sports Car Series season">2010 season</a>, Lexus departed from the Rolex Sports Car Series, and Ganassi Racing switched to <a href="/wiki/BMW" title="BMW">BMW</a>/<a href="/wiki/Dinan_Cars" title="Dinan Cars">Dinan</a> engines.<sup id="cite_ref-242" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-242">[242]</a></sup></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Lexus_LFA#Motorsport" title="Lexus LFA">LF-A prototype</a> also competed on the Nrburgring from 2008 to 2011 in <a href="/wiki/VLN" class="mw-redirect" title="VLN">VLN</a> endurance races<sup id="cite_ref-243" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-243">[243]</a></sup> and in the <a href="/wiki/24_Hours_N%C3%BCrburgring" title="24 Hours Nrburgring">24 Hours Nrburgring</a>, also with the IS F.<sup id="cite_ref-244" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-244">[244]</a></sup> On May 14, 2011, a CT 200h tuned up by Gazoo Racing competed in the Adenauer ADAC Rundstrecken-Trophy, a six-hour endurance race.<sup id="cite_ref-245" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-245">[245]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">Marketing</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lexus&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Marketing">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Futuristic two-door concept car displayed in front of a banner labeled &quot;Minority Report&quot;." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg/220px-Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg" width="220" height="127" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg/330px-Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg/440px-Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1043" data-file-height="601" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_2054_Minority_Report_concept1.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Lexus_2054" title="Lexus 2054">Lexus 2054</a>, a concept model produced for the film <i><a href="/wiki/Minority_Report_(film)" title="Minority Report (film)">Minority Report</a></i></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>From its inception, Lexus has been advertised to luxury consumers using specific <a href="/wiki/Marketing_strategy" title="Marketing strategy">marketing strategies</a>, with a consistent motif used for the marque's advertisements. Beginning in 1989, television ads were narrated by actor <a href="/wiki/James_Sloyan" title="James Sloyan">James Sloyan</a> (the voice of "Mr. Lexus" until 2009),<sup id="cite_ref-d118_30-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d118-30">[30]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-246" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-246">[246]</a></sup> and accompanied by vehicles that performed unusual stunts onscreen.<sup id="cite_ref-d119_247-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d119-247">[247]</a></sup> The first decade of Lexus commercials (198999) consisted primarily of disjunctive verbal descriptions, such as "relentless," "pursuit," and "perfection,"<sup id="cite_ref-248" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-248">[248]</a></sup> while vehicles were used to claim superiority in precision, idling, and interior quiet and comfort on camera.<sup id="cite_ref-d119_247-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d119-247">[247]</a></sup> Examples included the champagne glass "<a href="/wiki/Balance_(advertisement)" title="Balance (advertisement)">Balance</a>" (1989) and rolling "<a href="/wiki/Ball_Bearing_(advertisement)" title="Ball Bearing (advertisement)">Ball Bearing</a>" (1992).<sup id="cite_ref-d119_247-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-d119-247">[247]</a></sup> In the 2000s (decade), commercials included descriptions of features,<sup id="cite_ref-249" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-249">[249]</a></sup> or a narration of the events onscreen, and were often targeted at the marque's German competitors.<sup id="cite_ref-250" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-250">[250]</a></sup> An annual "December to Remember" campaign featured scenes of family members surprising loved ones with the gift of a new Lexus.<sup id="cite_ref-251" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-251">[251]</a></sup> The marque returned to the champagne glass theme in a 2006 LS 460 spot showing the sedan maneuvering between two stacks of glasses using its <a href="/wiki/Intelligent_Parking_Assist_System" title="Intelligent Parking Assist System">self-parking system</a>, and in a 2010 LFA spot showing its engine sound shattering a glass via <a href="/wiki/Resonance" title="Resonance">resonance</a> frequency.<sup id="cite_ref-glass_252-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-glass-252">[252]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Translucent glass model in the shape of a coupe." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg/220px-Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg/330px-Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg/440px-Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2571" data-file-height="1452" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lexus_LF-A_Crystallised_Wind.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Lexus_LFA#Sculpture_models" title="Lexus LFA">Lexus LFA Crystallised Wind</a>, a full-size glass art model</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Industry observers have attributed Lexus' early marketing successes to higher levels of perceived quality and lower prices than competitors, which have enabled the marque to attract customers upgrading from mass-market cars.<sup id="cite_ref-pr_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pr-6">[6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-zen_34-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zen-34">[34]</a></sup> A reputation for dependability, bolstered by reliability surveys, also became a primary factor in attracting new customers from rival premium makes.<sup id="cite_ref-253" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-253">[253]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-254" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-254">[254]</a></sup> Lexus has since grown to command higher <a href="/wiki/Premium_pricing" title="Premium pricing">price premiums</a> than rival Japanese makes,<sup id="cite_ref-lal_255-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lal-255">[255]</a></sup> with new models further increasing in price and reaching the more than $100,000 ultra-luxury category long dominated by rival European marques.<sup id="cite_ref-256" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-256">[256]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-257" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-257">[257]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-258" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-258">[258]</a></sup></p>
<p>Automotive analysts have also noted Lexus' relative newcomer status as a marketing challenge for the brand,<sup id="cite_ref-lsr_259-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lsr-259">[259]</a></sup> although some have debated the requirement of a long history.<sup id="cite_ref-lal_255-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lal-255">[255]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-260" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-260">[260]</a></sup> European rivals have marketed their decades of heritage and pedigree,<sup id="cite_ref-261" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-261">[261]</a></sup> whereas Lexus' reputation rests primarily upon its perceived quality and shared history with parent company Toyota.<sup id="cite_ref-lal_255-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lal-255">[255]</a></sup> Several analysts have stated that Lexus will have to develop its own heritage over time by highlighting technological innovations and producing substantial products.<sup id="cite_ref-global_94-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-global-94">[94]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lsr_259-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lsr-259">[259]</a></sup></p>
<p>Lexus' marketing efforts have extended to sporting and charity event sponsorships, including the <a href="/wiki/US_Open_(tennis)" title="US Open (tennis)">U.S. Open</a> tennis Grand Slam event from 2005 to 2009, and the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Golf_Association" title="United States Golf Association">United States Golf Association</a>'s <a href="/wiki/U.S._Open_(golf)" title="U.S. Open (golf)">U.S. Open</a>, <a href="/wiki/U.S._Women%27s_Open" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Women's Open">U.S. Women's Open</a>, <a href="/wiki/U.S._Senior_Open" title="U.S. Senior Open">U.S. Senior Open</a>, and <a href="/wiki/U.S._Amateur" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Amateur">U.S. Amateur</a> tournaments since 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-262" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-262">[262]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-263" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-263">[263]</a></sup> Lexus has organized an annual Champions for Charity golf series in the U.S. since 1989.<sup id="cite_ref-264" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-264">[264]</a></sup> Endorsement contracts have also been signed with professional athletes <a href="/wiki/Andy_Roddick" title="Andy Roddick">Andy Roddick</a>, <a href="/wiki/Annika_S%C3%B6renstam" title="Annika Srenstam">Annika Srenstam</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Peter_Jacobsen" title="Peter Jacobsen">Peter Jacobsen</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-265" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-265">[265]</a></sup></p>
<p>Lexus unveiled its new "Experience Amazing" tagline in the U.S. in a 60-second advertisement at the February 2017 <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_LI" title="Super Bowl LI">Super Bowl LI</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-266" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-266">[266]</a></sup> The new tagline replaced Lexus's previous slogan, "The Pursuit of Perfection".<sup id="cite_ref-267" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-267">[267]</a></sup></p>

New York: Free Press. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-7432-9017-8" title="Special:BookSources/0-7432-9017-8">0-7432-9017-8</a>. <a href="/wiki/Library_of_Congress_Control_Number" title="Library of Congress Control Number">LCCN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//lccn.loc.gov/2006048411">2006048411</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALexus&amp;rft.aufirst=Matthew+E.&amp;rft.aulast=May&amp;rft.btitle=The+Elegant+Solution%3A+Toyota%27s+Formula+for+Mastering+Innovation&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DuKc4D48LywgC%26printsec%3Dfrontcover&amp;rft_id=info%3Alccn%2F2006048411&amp;rft.isbn=0-7432-9017-8&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Free+Press&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
